{"id":"1hls8kup","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Light/dark mode: auto-detection + light/dark/auto toggle","description":"GOAL\n1. Auto-detect the OS color scheme and follow it.\n2. Add a user-facing toggle with three states: Light, Dark, Auto.\n3. Persist the selection end-to-end — from the web UI, through a Tauri command, into on-disk storage that survives app reload and relaunch.\n\nAuto-detection is already implicit — every *.css.ts uses `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` blocks. There is no theme store, no toggle, and no override mechanism yet.\n\nPERSISTENCE (firm requirement)\nThe selected mode (Light / Dark / Auto) must round-trip:\n- UI sets the mode -> invoke a Tauri command -> Rust writes to disk.\n- App launch -> Rust reads from disk -> UI hydrates from that value before first paint (to avoid a flash of the wrong theme).\n- Where exactly the value lives in src-tauri is open — likely a small persisted store next to the existing workspace storage; whatever fits cleanly with the current Rust architecture. Confirm the choice with me before implementing.\n- localStorage alone is not sufficient; it can supplement (e.g. as a same-session cache for fast first paint) but the source of truth lives on disk via Tauri.\n\nWORK WITH ME\nBefore writing code, propose an approach for these and get my sign-off:\n- Override strategy for CSS. The current `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` blocks only respond to the OS. Options worth comparing:\n  • A `data-theme` (or class) attribute on `<html>` plus selectors like `[data-theme='dark'] &` alongside the existing media query — minimal restructuring, but every dark block needs the extra selector.\n  • Vanilla Extract themes / contracts (createTheme / createThemeContract) — cleaner long-term, larger refactor of tokens.ts and every consumer.\n  • CSS custom properties driven by JS — flexible but moves styling out of the VE model the codebase prefers.\n- Where in src-tauri the persisted value lives, and the shape of the get/set commands.\n- Where the toggle lives in the UI. AppTopBar feels natural; confirm before placing it.\n- \"Auto\" semantics. Follow `prefers-color-scheme` live (listen to changes) vs. snapshot at app start. Live is the better UX but slightly more code.\n\nCONSTRAINTS\n- Vanilla Extract only; no hex outside tokens.ts.\n- Rust commands return Result with explicit errors (fail fast — do not panic on user paths).\n- Accessibility: the toggle should be keyboard-reachable and have an obvious label per state.\n- Avoid flash-of-wrong-theme on launch: resolve the saved preference before first paint.\n\nACCEPTANCE\n- Toggle with three states works: Light forces light, Dark forces dark, Auto follows OS (and updates live if OS preference changes).\n- Selection persists across full app restart (not just page reload), proven by quitting the app and reopening.\n- No flash of the wrong theme on launch.\n- All existing components still look right in both modes; no orphaned `@media` blocks that ignore the override.\n- No new lint / typecheck / fallow findings; clippy + rustfmt clean.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Shipped Light/Dark/Auto theme end-to-end: Tauri theme_mode in settings.json (get/set commands), index.html bootstrap + localStorage cache for first paint, data-theme + darkScheme CSS migration off prefers-color-scheme, AppTopBar cycle toggle with native window theme sync, and auto mode listening to OS changes. Verified check/typecheck/fallow/clippy locally.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-01T04:02:27.248Z","updated_at":"2026-06-01T08:18:11.204Z","started_at":"2026-06-01T05:40:04.796Z","completed_at":"2026-06-01T08:18:11.204Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
