{"id":"20au5fho","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"Fix engine audio crackle (loop layering + param ramping)","description":"Engine \"hum\" crackles on throttle and clips at load on Android Firefox. Root cause: engineIdle/engineThrust are the same engine-loop.ogg loaded into two three.Audio nodes — no timbral payoff, double the glitch surface (loop-seam phasing, coherent summing -> clipping). Plus updateEngine hard-sets volume/playbackRate every frame (instant AudioParam jumps = zipper noise). Fix: decide one-loop-node vs. two genuinely-distinct files; pre-set initial loop volumes BEFORE play() so startup does not double-clip; ramp volume/playbackRate via setTargetAtTime instead of three's instant setVolume/setPlaybackRate. Contained to createGameAudio.ts / engineAudio.ts; keep computeEngineLayerState math.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Firefox mobile crackle fixed on audio-improvements branch. Root cause was loop wrap seam on engine-loop-seamless.ogg; measured loopStart/loopEnd (sample 4_884_761 at 44.1 kHz) fixes it. Also simplified single-loop throttle→pitch mapping, removed per-frame gain/rate ramps, added playback-rate dedup, seamless mono asset. Dropped manual listener sync and two-node crossfade after A/B (crackle returned). Merged to branch: loop boundaries, ENGINE_LOOP_END_SECONDS rate-independent splice.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-25T01:48:51.751Z","updated_at":"2026-06-25T04:43:13.623Z","started_at":"2026-06-25T01:50:24.853Z","completed_at":"2026-06-25T04:43:13.623Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"27bj688a","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"Repo-wide: drop .ts/.tsx import extensions (go extensionless)","description":"Flip the import convention from explicit .ts/.tsx suffixes to extensionless (the mainstream norm and the preferred style). This reverses the currently-documented standard in AGENTS.md, so do it deliberately as its own PR, not mixed with netcode work.\n\nScope:\n- Codemod every import specifier (#/ alias imports and any relative imports) to drop the .ts/.tsx suffix across all workspaces (apps/client, apps/server, packages/shared, tools/*).\n- Flip allowImportingTsExtensions off in tsconfig.base.json. Confirm moduleResolution: bundler still resolves extensionless .ts/.tsx (it should); keep verbatimModuleSyntax on.\n- Update AGENTS.md import rules (the .ts/.tsx-suffix requirement around the Imports section, the vanilla-extract .css.ts import note, and the monorepo-consistency paragraph that references the flag).\n- Add or adjust a lint rule to enforce extensionless imports so the new convention is gated, not just documented.\n- Validate: vp check, vp test, and fallow audit all green.\n\nReason: extensionless is less noisy, matches the overwhelming TS convention, and lets .ts<->.tsx renames happen without touching importers. The explicit-suffix style was a deliberate but minority choice enabled by allowImportingTsExtensions; we are choosing the mainstream style instead.","priority":1,"completed":false,"result":null,"metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-27T23:35:53.992Z","updated_at":"2026-06-27T23:35:53.992Z","started_at":null,"completed_at":null,"blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"2evkv6xf","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"Multiplayer netcode: server-authoritative dogfighting","description":"Add online multiplayer to Scriptlancer (currently single-player, three.js + @dimforge/rapier3d-deterministic-compat). Target: smooth dogfights, 2 players for testing, scaling toward 32+ in one room; possible MMO later but explicitly deferred.\n\nMODEL DECIDED (NOT rollback): server-authoritative simulation + client-side prediction of the LOCAL ship only + entity interpolation for remote ships (~100ms behind) + lag-compensated hit detection. Rollback/GGPO was rejected (a 2-player technique; re-simulating a full Rapier world per correction does not scale to 32). This model means bit-for-bit client/server determinism is NOT required — drift is smoothly corrected.\n\nSTACK DECIDED: TypeScript end-to-end. Server runs on Bun (WebTransport via webtransport-bun; Bun.serve has no first-class WebTransport yet) and reuses the SAME Rapier WASM module as the client, so there is one physics codebase. Gleam/BEAM + Rust + rustler NIF was rejected (NIF defeats BEAM fault isolation; tri-lingual serialization; not worth it once bit-determinism was not needed). Keep the deterministic Rapier build (helps reproducible server sims + prediction closeness) but it is now convenient, not load-bearing.\n\nCLOCKS: fixed 60Hz sim tick, ~20Hz snapshot broadcast, render at display rate (interpolated). These three rates are independent.\n\nWIRE PROTOCOL: hand-rolled binary codec over DataView/ArrayBuffer in packages/shared, imported by both client and server. Byte savings via quantization (float32/int16 positions, quaternion smallest-three), delta snapshots vs acked baseline, input bit-packing. No protobuf/flatbuffers/msgpack on the hot path.\n\nTRANSPORT DECIDED: WebTransport (HTTP/3 over QUIC) from the start — NOT WebSocket. Rationale: unreliable datagrams for state (no TCP head-of-line blocking under packet loss) PLUS reliable ordered streams for lobby/events on one connection; clean API with none of WebRTC signaling pain. Verified Baseline as of Safari 26.4 (iOS + macOS, ~March 2026); Chrome 97+/Edge 98+/Firefox 114+ already had it; ~85% global coverage. iOS support is recent, so a long tail of un-updated devices lacks it — keep transport behind a thin Transport interface (sendUnreliable/sendReliable/onMessage) so a WebSocket or WebRTC-DataChannel fallback for that tail stays a config swap, not a rewrite. Bun has no first-class WebTransport in Bun.serve yet; use the webtransport-bun package (N-API addon backed by the Rust wtransport crate — a contained transport dep, NOT game logic). Transport is decoupled from Phases 0-6 (sim/prediction/interpolation/protocol are transport-agnostic); it concretely lands in Phase 2 and affects deploy in Phase 7. The big perceived-quality wins are prediction + interpolation + lag comp; WebTransport is robustness polish, committed up front rather than scaffolding throwaway WebSocket.\n\nSTRUCTURE DECIDED: convert the flat single-package repo into a Vite+ / Bun-workspace monorepo, based on the Vite+ monorepo template (node_modules/vite-plus/templates/monorepo). Layout: apps/client (the current src/ — three.js, Preact, Vite+, GLB/OGG assets, wrangler), apps/server (Bun + webtransport-bun, rooms, matchmaking), packages/shared (sim core, protocol, types, math, collider defs — NO three.js, NO DOM), tools/ later. Root package.json gets the workspaces field + ready / vp run -r scripts; root vite.config.ts holds shared fmt/lint/check + run.cache with lint/fmt OVERRIDES per package (client: preact/glsl; server: env node). App-specific vite config (rapier optimizeDeps pre-bundle, rolldown vendor code-splitting, glsl, assetsInclude) moves into apps/client/vite.config.ts. #/* subpath imports stay PER-PACKAGE; shared is consumed by package name. WHAT IS ACTUALLY SHARED: only CODE (sim/protocol/types/collider defs) — the 3.4M of GLB/OGG art is client-only; the server never renders or plays audio. SEQUENCING: the mechanical monorepo move (Phase 0.5) is kept separate from the sim extraction (Phase 1) so each diff is legible. Do NOT scaffold a fresh repo with vp create — adopt the template structure into the existing repo to preserve git history, the tuned vite.config, and wrangler.\n\nHOSTING DECIDED: Bun on Fly.io (persistent micro-VMs, scale-to-zero, Machines API to spawn room servers); Cloudflare Worker + Hono for the stateless lobby/matchmaker. Edge/serverless rejected for the sim (stateful, never-sleeping tick loop). PartyKit rejected for the sim (Durable Object CPU model fights a continuous tick + it is WebSocket-based). Local/offline play reuses the server sim module in-process.\n\nCURRENT STATE TO REFACTOR: the game loop at src/game/scriptlancer.ts:409 is a single render-driven loop stepping Rapier with variable dt — must split into fixed-tick sim + interpolated render. Server-side authority must absorb what the client currently does locally: AI pilot, weapon fire, hit detection, damage, collisions. colliderFromObject.ts derives colliders from three.js meshes and must be reworked into three.js-free shared collider definitions.\n\nChildren are sequential, independently testable phases: 0, 0.5, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7.\n\nNOTE: The temporary 3-way client split (default / ?sharedsim / ?server=) is intentional scaffolding. It is consolidated in task l2mowwvj — one client shell + swappable sim-source, retiring the parallel sims — after Phases 3-4.","priority":1,"completed":false,"result":null,"metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-26T08:40:38.989Z","updated_at":"2026-06-28T06:21:10.642Z","started_at":"2026-06-26T20:19:44.414Z","completed_at":null,"blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":["zu5cxe3q","9561xh4k","k3zbaseh","31gfijwz","yc43t68n","w4uplxdh","r0kwsu7b","irrxwdh3","13hd0wi5","r7m8cdls","5fn4vdf4","l2mowwvj","kirrckfk","03trbq7o","s75011q0","7doslvmi"]}
