{"id":"dh34x9uy","parent_id":"jvprxjqg","name":"UI: ingredient name vs amount vs note","description":"## Goal\nPreview and saved-recipe views make it **easy to audit** ingredient lines before saying “yes” — supports the human gate in parent `jvprxjqg`.\n\n## Why\nGreg needs to spot wrong names, merged notes, and bad qty/unit at a glance. If the preview is muddy, we’ll confirm bad data into Turso.\n\n## Today\n- Query + detail: `name — qty unit note` as one gray suffix; notes look like part of the name.\n\n## Work\n1. Shared line layout: **name** prominent; **qty + unit** secondary; **note** visually distinct (sub-line / italic — match app).\n2. Apply on `/query` preview and `/recipe/$recipeId`.\n3. Payload unchanged (name, quantity, unit, note still separate in API).\n\n## Acceptance\n- Notes never read as the canonical ingredient name.\n- Greg can review a full ingredient list without opening raw JSON/markdown.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Shared RecipeIngredientLine: bold name, secondary qty+unit, italic note on query preview and recipe detail.","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"0e29fe7","message":"more and more links","branch":"import-confirm-ui-polish","timestamp":"2026-05-18T06:17:33.458Z"}},"created_at":"2026-05-18T04:18:44.687Z","updated_at":"2026-05-18T06:17:33.460Z","started_at":"2026-05-18T06:17:33.459Z","completed_at":"2026-05-18T06:17:33.460Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"dhxslqre","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Collapsed sidebar: deterministic per-workspace visual distinction","description":"GOAL\nWhen the workspace sidebar is collapsed, each item should be visually distinguishable at a glance — not just by its initial letter (current behavior in src/components/WorkspaceSidebar/CollapsedWorkspaceList.tsx). Derive the distinction deterministically from the workspace name so the same workspace always looks the same across sessions and machines.\n\nCURRENT STATE\n- Collapsed item = 2rem square, first letter of name, single accent color for active/hover (workspaceSidebar.css.ts: collapsedWorkspaceSquare / ...Active).\n- Workspace shape: { id, name, configPath, storagePath } (src/schemas/workspace.ts).\n- Palette today is a small curated set in src/styles/tokens.ts — no rainbow swatch palette exists yet.\n\nAPPROACH (to decide during the work)\n- Deterministic hash of `workspace.name` -> index into a small palette (and/or icon set). Simple string hash (FNV-1a or djb2) is plenty; document the choice inline.\n- Prefer CSS-only application: compute a class or CSS variable per item, drive bg / border / accent text via that. JS does the hash; CSS does the painting. Define swatches as a Vanilla Extract style map in workspaceSidebar.css.ts (or a new module under src/styles/) using palette tokens — do not hard-code hex outside tokens.ts.\n- Keep light + dark mode working; pick swatches with enough contrast against both surface and surfaceDark, and against the active border.\n\nOPEN DESIGN QUESTIONS (resolve before/during implementation)\n1. Color vs icon vs both? Start with color (smallest change, fewest assets). Revisit icons only if color alone is not distinct enough.\n2. Should workspace names be required to be unique? Today nothing enforces it — if two workspaces share a name they would hash to the same swatch. Decide whether to (a) enforce uniqueness in the add-workspace flow (src/components/WorkspaceSidebar/AddWorkspacePanel.tsx + the Rust command), or (b) accept rare collisions and rely on the letter + tooltip to disambiguate.\n3. Neighbor-collision avoidance? With ~6–10 swatches and a hash, adjacent items can occasionally land on the same color. Options: ignore it (simplest), nudge to the next swatch when a neighbor collides (small post-pass in CollapsedWorkspaceList), or pick a palette size that makes collisions visually fine. Default to \"ignore unless it looks bad in practice.\"\n\nCONSTRAINTS / STYLE\n- Vanilla Extract only — no inline style objects beyond a single CSS-variable assignment if needed for dynamic indexing.\n- Functional helpers with early returns; no forEach.\n- Keep the hashing helper small and pure, colocated with CollapsedWorkspaceList or under src/lib/ if reused elsewhere. JSDoc one-liner on the export.\n- Respect existing accessibility: aria-label and title already carry the full name; the color is decorative — do not remove the letter.\n\nACCEPTANCE\n- Each collapsed sidebar item has a stable color derived from its name.\n- Light + dark modes both look intentional; active state still reads as active.\n- No new lint / typecheck / fallow findings; no hex literals outside tokens.ts.\n- A short note in AGENTS.md (or this task's followup) if we landed on a convention worth remembering (e.g. \"palette swatches live in styles/workspaceSwatches.css.ts\").","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Collapsed sidebar: deterministic per-workspace pastel letter colors.\n\n- FNV-1a hash of trimmed/lowercased workspace name → index into palette in tokens.ts\n- VE letter class map (workspaceSwatches.css.ts) + workspaceSwatch.ts helper\n- CollapsedWorkspaceList applies swatch classes on initials span (avoids global button color)\n- add_workspace rejects exact duplicate names (trimmed); duplicate check trims stored names too\n- Co-located workspaceSwatch.test.ts; Vitest wired as first test file","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-01T02:22:39.835Z","updated_at":"2026-06-01T05:27:48.51