{"id":"hl9qg145","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"AI combat positioning: Face / Trail / Buzz state graph","description":"Add a lightweight combat positioning state machine for the AI pursuer before NPC\nweapons: weighted transitions among Face (point at target), Trail (tail-chase /\nstandoff pursuit), and Buzz (timed pass-by vector), each selecting a pursuit\npoint that feeds the existing Pilot steering + asteroid avoidance stack.\n\nReference Librelancer SNPCComponent's Face / Trail / Buzz loop for behavior\nshape, but implement as our own model — no Freelancer/Librelancer names in code\nor comments (per project convention).\n\nContext (after bcohudeg):\n- createAiPilot runs continuous tail-chase + heading-nudge avoidance.\n- pursuitTarget.ts: seekTargetFromPosition, tailChaseTarget.\n- Pilot.step → shared stepSteering → applyControls (never bypass physics limits).\n\nSuggested steps:\n1. Pure state graph types + transition table (per-edge weights, minimum dwell\n   time). Unit-test transitions with injected RNG so rolls are deterministic in\n   tests.\n2. Face: pursuit point on the pursued ship (optional lead-prediction stub for a\n   later weapons task — no shooting here).\n3. Trail: reuse tailChaseTarget or Goto-style standoff radius (configurable\n   offset behind pursued forward).\n4. Buzz: pick a pass-by offset in pursued-local space, seek it for a timed\n   slice, then allow transition out (distance- or timer-based).\n5. Integrate into createAiPilot or a thin createCombatPilot wrapper: state\n   picks base pursuit point; blendTargetWithAvoidance still runs afterward.\n6. Demoable in-game: AI visibly alternates behaviors while chasing the player.\n\nDependencies: bcohudeg. Complements jke0r8bn (player weapons) and a future NPC\nweapons task — do not add gun logic in this milestone.\n\nTuning: per-behavior distances, dwell times, and transition weights as codified\nknobs with handicapped defaults so beginners can still shake a tail.\n\nConventions: AGENTS.md. Validate vp check → vp test → fallow:audit.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Face/Trail/Buzz combat positioning state machine in combatState.ts; integrated into createAiPilot with pursuit helpers; 137 tests pass.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-25T05:34:49.651Z","updated_at":"2026-06-25T06:41:29.333Z","started_at":"2026-06-25T06:16:41.545Z","completed_at":"2026-06-25T06:41:29.333Z","blockedBy":["bcohudeg"],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"hwyhgcu3","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Resizable divider between task list and task detail (with @preact/signals)","description":"GOAL\nAdd a draggable column divider between TaskBoard (middle column) and TaskDetail (right pane) inside WorkspaceMain. Width should clamp to sensible min/max, persist across app restart, and feel native — no flicker, no re-render storm during drag, full keyboard support.\n\nDECISION: BESPOKE IMPLEMENTATION\nWe are building this ourselves. No npm dependency for the resizer — not react-resizable-panels, not allotment, not anything similar. The implementation is ~80 lines of native PointerEvents + CSS Grid + a typed @property + @preact/signals. Reasons, explicit so we do not relitigate:\n- Vanilla Extract integration with a library that generates its own classNames is ongoing friction.\n- The library's biggest \"free\" win is persistence — and we need Tauri-on-disk persistence, not browser storage, so that win evaporates.\n- One divider does not justify a dependency. The codebase aesthetic (AGENTS.md) leans small and owned.\n- The Preact-compat shim is the codebase's first reach for it; precedent matters.\n\nWHEN TO REVISIT THIS DECISION\nMigrate to react-resizable-panels (and delete the bespoke Resizer) the FIRST time any of these lands:\n- A second resizable boundary (vertical split inside TaskDetail, third column, nested panel groups).\n- A need for snap points, collapse-to-min with imperative control, or panel reordering.\n- An accessibility audit finding we cannot fix in <1 day inside the bespoke handler.\nDo NOT duplicate the bespoke Resizer for a second boundary. Add a comment in the Resizer file pointing at this clause so future-us sees the trigger.\n\nCHOSEN APPROACH (signals-first)\nThis task adopts @preact/signals for the ephemeral drag state. Signals are not used anywhere else in the codebase yet — this is the first foothold and worth a short ADR note (in AGENTS.md or a follow-up) so the pattern is intentional, not accidental.\n\nWhy signals here (vs. useState / Zustand):\n- Drag updates fire ~60 Hz. useState would re-render the component every frame; Zustand would re-render every consumer of the width.\n- Signals give fine-grained reactivity: only the bit of DOM that reads the signal updates. The cursor / aria-valuenow / data-dragging flag can bind to the signal without re-rendering TaskBoard or TaskDetail.\n- The committed (post-drag) width still lives in Zustand and persists via Tauri — signals own the live drag, Zustand owns the durable state.\n\nWORK WITH ME\nConfirm with me before implementing:\n- The signals adoption itself — happy to make this the first signals usage, but I want to acknowledge it.\n- Persistence layer: this should reuse whatever prefs mechanism comes out of task 1hls8kup (theme persistence). If 1hls8kup has not landed yet, decide whether to (a) block on it, (b) introduce a minimal prefs command we both consume, or (c) ship width-in-memory first and persist later.\n\nTECHNICAL RECIPE (2026)\nLayout in src/views/views.css.ts — switch .workspaceMain from flex row to CSS Grid:\n  gridTemplateColumns: 'var(--task-board-width, 13rem) auto 1fr'\n  (auto = the resizer handle column; 1fr = TaskDetail)\nDrop the hard-coded `flex: '0 1 13rem'` / `maxWidth: '16rem'` from `.board` in src/components/TaskList/taskList.css.ts; width is owned by the grid container var.\n\nRegister the custom property so it is typed and animatable:\n  globalStyle('@property --task-board-width', { syntax: '<length>', inherits: false, initialValue: '13rem' })\n\nResizer component (new — src/components/WorkspaceResizer/ ...):\n- role=\\\"separator\\\", aria-orientation=\\\"vertical\\\", aria-valuenow/min/max, aria-controls=\\\"task-board\\\", tabIndex=0\n- onPointerDown -> setPointerCapture, capture startX + startWidth into signals\n- onPointerMove -> compute clamped width, write directly to container.style.setProperty('--task-board-width', \\`\\${w}px\\`) via a ref. NO setState, NO Zustand write during drag.\n- onPointerUp -> release capture, commit final width to Zustand, debounced Tauri persist\n- Keyboard (APG splitter pattern): Arrow keys nudge ±8px, Home/End jump to min/max, Enter cycles snap positions (e.g. default 13rem).\n- touchAction: 'none' on the handle; user-select: none on body during drag.\n\nUse @preact/signals for ephemeral drag state:\n- isDragging signal -> drives cursor / data attribute for styling, without re-rendering panes.\n- liveWidth signal -> updated on each move so aria-valuenow stays accurate; reads cheap because only the separator binds to it.\n\nAdd container queries on the panes (src/components/TaskBoard/* and src/components/TaskDetail/*):\n- containerType: 'inline-size' on the pane roots\n- @container (max-width: 9rem) { /* compact mode for TaskBoard */ }\n- @container (max-width: 24rem) { /* condensed metadata in TaskDetail */ }\nThis way each pane self-adjusts as the user drags, no JS ResizeObserver needed.\n\nOptional polish: View Transitions API on double-click-reset.\n  if (document.startViewTransition) document.startViewTransition(() => setWidth(DEFAULT));\nGraceful fallback to instant on older runtimes.\n\nCONSTRAINTS\n- Vanilla Extract only; no hex outside tokens.ts.\n- No inline style objects beyond setting CSS custom properties via ref.\n- Functional helpers, early returns, no forEach.\n- Light + dark modes both look intentional; the handle is visible-but-quiet at rest, clearly interactive on hover/focus.\n- Window resize must clamp current width into [MIN, container-width - DETAIL_MIN].\n\nACCEPTANCE\n- Dragging the divider resizes TaskBoard and TaskDetail smoothly at 60fps with no React re-renders during the drag (verified via Preact devtools / a profiler check).\n- Width persists across app restart.\n- Keyboard fully works per APG splitter pattern.\n- Container queries kick in on the panes themselves as width crosses thresholds.\n- No new lint / typecheck / fallow findings; clippy + rustfmt clean.\n- @preact/signals is added as a dependency, with a brief note in AGENTS.md on when to reach for signals vs. Zustand vs. useState.\n- No new dependency for the resizer itself (see DECISION: BESPOKE IMPLEMENTATION).","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Shipped via PR #19 (resizable-pane). Bespoke WorkspaceResizer with PointerEvents + CSS Grid + @preact/signals for ephemeral drag state; committed width persisted via Zustand/Tauri. @preact/signals added with an AGENTS.md note. One open follow-up: divider styling currently reads as a macOS scrollbar (0.5rem wide, fully rounded) — tracked separately.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-01T07:17:59.314Z","updated_at":"2026-06-02T15:38:57.500Z","started_at":"2026-06-01T08:19:11.945Z","completed_at":"2026-06-02T15:38:57.500Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
