{"id":"jax4mb7b","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Quick prompts: keyboard select + copy","description":"Keyboard shortcuts for the inline Quick prompts panel (task detail + workspace home).\n\n## Goals\n\n1. **Select by number** — `$mod+1` … `$mod+4` select the corresponding quick prompt by **display order** (same order as the `<select>`). Fixed slot mapping: slot 1 = first prompt in the list, slot 2 = second, etc. Unused slots on a given view (e.g. workspace home has only 2 prompts) are no-ops.\n\n2. **Unavailable prompts** — If the prompt at that slot is disabled (`isAvailable: false`), the shortcut does nothing (no skip-to-next, no fallback).\n\n3. **Copy** — `$mod+C` copies the **currently selected** prompt text to the clipboard and shows the same visual affordance as the toolbar copy button (checkmark / “Copied!” via existing `useClipboardCopy` feedback). Do **not** copy when changing selection.\n\n4. **No manual focus** — Shortcuts work while the user is in a keyboard-driven flow (e.g. task list focus, detail visible) without requiring focus inside the Quick prompts panel. Still respect existing guards: no hijack while typing in an editable field or while the workspace sidebar owns focus.\n\n5. **Surfaces** — Task detail (`TaskDetailQuickPrompts`) and workspace home (`WorkspaceHomeQuickPrompts`) only. **Out of scope:** the task-list right-click context menu (`TaskAgentPromptMenu` / `farzygud`) — that menu copies immediately on pick and has no inline preview.\n\n6. **Cross-platform** — Use `$mod` (⌘ on macOS, Ctrl on Windows/Linux), consistent with other gdex chrome shortcuts.\n\n## UX notes\n\n- Update the `<select>` and code block when a number shortcut fires.\n- Document new shortcuts in `README.md` (keyboard shortcuts table).\n- Avoid conflicting with task-list navigation (`j`/`k`, etc.) and existing chrome bindings.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- From task detail with quick prompts visible: `$mod+1`…`4` switch selection per rules above; `$mod+C` copies active prompt with button-equivalent feedback.\n- From workspace home: `$mod+1`/`2` select list/create; `$mod+3`/`4` no-op; `$mod+C` copies selection.\n- Disabled prompts (e.g. Start on in-progress task) ignore their slot shortcut.\n- Works without clicking into the Quick prompts panel first.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Added ⌘1–4 slot selection and ⌘C copy for inline Quick prompts (task detail + workspace home). Shortcuts work without panel focus; unavailable slots no-op; guards defer while typing, sidebar focused, or context menu open. README updated; unit tests for slot/text helpers.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-06T23:25:44.910Z","updated_at":"2026-06-07T00:28:11.880Z","started_at":"2026-06-06T23:27:40.539Z","completed_at":"2026-06-07T00:28:11.880Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"jc14dzcw","parent_id":"mzb84gnf","name":"Investigation: batch ingredient evaluation to reduce LLM cost","description":"Goal: add batched Claude ingredient picks that compose existing per-ingredient goldens (ktdpt2fi), reducing LLM calls without duplicating Spoonacular fixtures.\n\nPrerequisite (done): ktdpt2fi — 10 individual *.spoonacular.json + *.expected.json; spoonacular:ingredient:pick:golden passes.\n\nApproach:\n- Individual goldens remain source of truth for candidates and acceptable picks\n- Batch fixtures only list member slugs (inheritance); expected derived from each member's *.expected.json\n- Target batch size: 5 per case; 2 batch cases from the 10 individuals (mixed difficulty)\n- New harness: spoonacular:ingredient:pick:batch:golden (Claude only, no Spoonacular)\n\nQuestions to answer:\n- Prompt/schema for N independent picks in one structured response\n- Failure modes (cross-item poisoning, especially no_match items like ti-leaves)\n- Token/cost tradeoffs vs per-item calls\n- Go/no-go for production batching\n\nDone when all subtasks complete.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Batched ingredient pick investigation complete: inheritance-based batch manifests (2×5), pickSpoonacularIngredientCandidatesBatchWithClaude + schema, test:ai:spoonacular:ingredient:pick:batch:golden passes. Design doc with go/no-go in batches/README.md. Finding: batch prompt must match single-item judgment (belacan case). Prod batching deferred pending go/no-go.","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"1dbeb206b2234eda43a073f365f9b88145b2248c","message":":wrench: batches","branch":"recipe-claude","timestamp":"2026-05-16T20:07:29.741Z"}},"created_at":"2026-05-07T07:26:26.771Z","updated_at":"2026-05-16T21:43:30.215Z","started_at":"2026-05-16T19:57:21.319Z","completed_at":"2026-05-16T20:07:29.743Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":["hxvfv6wg","jquijs2j","19lb8s7o","clmoyf5n"]}
{"id":"jcaiem4g","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Show completed tasks in subtask list","description":"In the subtask/task list view, completed (non-archived) tasks should remain visible rather than disappearing. This gives the user a sense of progress and lets them reference recently completed work without losing context.\n\n## Sort order\n\nTasks render in three groups, top to bottom:\n\n1. **In-progress** (`[>]`) — actively being worked on, at the very top\n2. **Incomplete** (`[ ]`) — open work, not yet started\n3. **Complete** (`[x]`) — finished work, at the bottom\n\nWithin each group, existing priority/ordering rules apply (e.g. priority `-p` value, then creation order). Active work always sits above finished work.\n\n## Visual treatment\n\nCompleted tasks should look visibly done — muted color, strikethrough on the title, or similar — to match how the dex CLI renders `[x]` items. They should read as \"context, not action\" at a glance.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- **Archived tasks remain hidden.** This change is about completed-but-not-archived only.\n- No change to filtering controls, search, or the count badges in headers (revisit separately if needed).","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Fetch completed tasks via dex list --all --json; sort task lists in_progress → pending → done before priority/name. Done styling already present in TaskList and TaskDetail.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-05-23T04:52:22.683Z","updated_at":"2026-05-23T05:11:25.596Z","started_at":"2026-05-23T05:11:25.594Z","completed_at":"2026-05-23T05:11:25.596Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"jke0r8bn","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"Projectile weapons with Freelancer/Librelancer-style aiming","description":"Add ship projectile weapons that fire and aim like Freelancer/Librelancer: guns converge toward the aiming reticle within gun-arc limits, with a dynamic lead/target indicator for moving targets.\n\nNorth star: Freelancer and Librelancer are the DREAM for how targeting should work (gun convergence plus the dynamic lead reticle for intercepting moving targets). Treat their behavior as the reference to aim for, even though the first landable slice is simpler.\n\nContext (current code):\n- Ship is a three.js Group with position + quaternion; forward = (0,0,-1).applyQuaternion(quaternion). See src/game/loadModel.ts.\n- Steering/aim in src/game/controls/flyByWire.ts. The aim cone is centered on the ship forward axis via aimQuat = lookRotation(shipForward, cameraUp) in snapshotAim, so the static HUD center marker is a truthful boresight (where straight shots go). The movable diamond reticle is the steering cursor, offset from boresight.\n- Linear velocity lives in shipThrustState.velocity inside the attachFlyByWire closure (src/game/physics/shipThrust.ts). Projectiles should inherit ship velocity, so this must be exposed/lifted out of the closure (shared ship-state object or ship.userData).\n- HUD overlay: src/game/hud/reticleHud.ts (ortho scene; diamond reticle + static center marker). A lead indicator would be a new HUD element.\n- Sim loop: single renderer.setAnimationLoop with clamped dt in src/game/scriptlancer.ts; flightControls.update(dt) advances input/steering/thrust/camera.\n\nSuggested steps:\n1. Boresight MVP to validate the pipeline: a pure physics/projectile.ts (stepProjectile: position += velocity*dt, TTL/max-range) plus an effectful pool/spawner; spawn at ship position along forward, inheriting ship velocity; fire on mousedown while engaged with a fire-rate clock. Colocate projectile.test.ts. Mirror shipThrust.ts/shipSteering.ts patterns and three.js dispose rules - pool/reuse geometry+material, dispose on teardown.\n2. Spawn from model hardpoints/gun mounts instead of ship center: extract named hardpoint nodes from the glTF (or define mount offsets) around loadModel.ts.\n3. Freelancer-style convergence: angle each gun shot toward the reticle aim point within gun-arc limits.\n4. Lead targeting: once targets exist, compute the intercept point from target position/velocity + projectile speed and render a dynamic lead reticle.\n\nDependencies/notes: full lead targeting needs a target/enemy + hit-detection system that does not exist yet, so boresight firing + convergence can land first. Velocity inheritance requires exposing ship velocity from flyByWire.\n\nConventions: #/ imports with .ts suffix, type over interface, undefined over null, @sideEffect tags, pure tested math, no three.js in the UI layer, dispose all GPU resources. Validate with vp check then vp test (and bun run fallow:audit). See AGENTS.md.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Projectile weapons: bolt pool with hardpoint spawn, ship-velocity inheritance, gun-arc convergence toward aim reticle, lead intercept + HUD lead/target indicators, asteroid and AI-ship collision. vp check and vp test (169) pass.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-21T16:57:03.888Z","updated_at":"2026-06-25T08:39:00.241Z","started_at":"2026-06-25T07:08:20.302Z","completed_at":"2026-06-25T08:39:00.241Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"jlt8n1ot","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Cap quick prompt code block height","description":"GOAL\nQuick prompt code blocks can grow very tall when prompt text is long, consuming excessive vertical space in the task detail pane and workspace home panel. Today the whole **Quick prompts** section is collapsible via a `<details>` disclosure, but when expanded a long prompt still dominates the layout. Add a max-height cap on the prompt `<pre>` with vertical scrolling so expanded panels stay compact.\n\nPROBLEM\nAgent prompt strings (built in `src/lib/agentPrompts.ts`) can be multi-paragraph instructions. `AgentPromptCodeBlock` renders them in a `<pre>` with `whiteSpace: pre-wrap` and no height limit — the block grows to fit all content. Users must collapse the entire Quick prompts section to reclaim space; there is no in-panel scroll.\n\nCURRENT UI (starting points)\n- **Shared panel:** `src/components/QuickPrompts/QuickPromptsPanel.tsx` — `<details>` disclosure wrapper, prompt `<select>`, then `AgentPromptCodeBlock`. Used by:\n  - `src/components/TaskDetail/QuickPrompts/TaskDetailQuickPrompts.tsx` (task detail)\n  - `src/components/WorkspaceHomePanel/WorkspaceHomeQuickPrompts.tsx` (workspace home)\n- **Code block:** `src/components/TaskDetail/QuickPrompts/AgentPromptCodeBlock.tsx` — flex row: `<pre>` (text) + toolbar (copy button).\n- **Styles:** `src/components/TaskDetail/QuickPrompts/taskDetailQuickPrompts.css.ts` — `quickPromptCode`, `quickPromptCodeText`, `quickPromptStack` (parent has `overflow: hidden`; verify scroll still works after changes).\n\nPRECEDENT\nTask description disclosure in `src/components/TaskDetail/TaskDetail.tsx` treats copy longer than ~10 lines / 500 chars as “long” and starts collapsed. A similar ~10-line visual cap is a reasonable default for prompt code blocks unless UX testing suggests otherwise — pick one constant and document it in CSS or a named constant if shared.\n\nREQUIREMENTS\n1. Limit the prompt text area to a sane max height (roughly 8–12 lines of `quickPromptCodeText` at its current `fontSize` / `lineHeight`).\n2. When content exceeds the cap, show a vertical scrollbar on the text area (`overflow-y: auto`), not on the whole panel.\n3. Keep the copy button toolbar visible without scrolling — it sits beside the `<pre>` today; preserve that layout.\n4. Apply to all `AgentPromptCodeBlock` usages (task detail + workspace home share the same component/styles).\n5. Collapsible `<details>` behavior stays as-is; this is additive.\n6. Match existing light/dark styling (`palette.codeBlockBg`, etc.); scrollbar appearance should not look broken in either theme.\n\nOUT OF scope\n- Right-click **Quick prompts** context menu (`TaskAgentPromptMenu`) — different UI, no shared code block.\n- Changing prompt copy in `agentPrompts.ts`.\n- Task **Description** disclosure / truncation (separate feature in `TaskDetail.tsx`).\n- Horizontal scrolling, line numbers, or “expand to full height” toggle (unless trivial to add with the scroll container).\n\nDONE WHEN\n- Long prompts show a scrollable `<pre>` capped at the chosen max height.\n- Short prompts unchanged (no unnecessary scrollbar gutter).\n- Copy button works and remains reachable while text scrolls.\n- `bun run check` and `bun run typecheck` pass.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Capped AgentPromptCodeBlock at 5 lines with thin themed scrollbar; quick prompts always expanded (removed isInitiallyOpen). Also: description in 10-line scroll box, auto-collapse only when subtasks exist, TaskDetailContent keyed by task.id for fresh disclosure state.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-06T19:34:52.330Z","updated_at":"2026-06-06T19:49:57.119Z","started_at":"2026-06-06T19:36:37.031Z","completed_at":"2026-06-06T19:49:57.119Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
