{"id":"kirrckfk","parent_id":"2evkv6xf","name":"Move human steering controller into the shared sim (raw view-relative input over the wire)","description":"DO AS PART OF / ALONGSIDE PHASE 5 (w4uplxdh). Folded out of l2mowwvj on 2026-06-29 (dex max-depth blocks nesting under w4uplxdh, so it sits as a sibling). Make the server authoritative over steering from RAW view-relative intent instead of the client sending the controller's torque demand. CORRECTED RATIONALE: the original 'PID-state desync -> waver' premise does NOT hold. The steering PIDs (createSteeringController) are proportional-only (ki=0,kd=0), i.e. stateless, so replaying the localSteering output during reconciliation is already deterministic; the waver was a separate issue (reconciliation rotation offset leaking into the camera/bank reference) and is already fixed. localSteering is also already clamped to [-1,1] per axis, so steering is already anti-cheat-bounded. NET: low value today; real home is Phase 5 server-authority/anti-cheat. SCOPE IF DONE: steering is view-relative (the human pilot derives ship-local aim from cursor influence + camera aimQuat and banks relative to camera referenceUp), so 'send raw input' means putting the camera aim-direction + view-up on the wire (replacing ShipControlInput.localSteering), moving localAimFromInfluence + stepSteering into tickShipSim, and reworking how createAiPilot feeds steering. Touches shared sim + codec + server + both pilots.","priority":1,"completed":false,"result":null,"metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-29T23:50:53.047Z","updated_at":"2026-06-30T04:51:55.366Z","started_at":"2026-06-30T04:51:55.364Z","completed_at":null,"blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"krkpzjdq","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Full keyboard navigation (vim + arrows, expanding from there)","description":"GOAL\nMake gdex fully usable from the keyboard — no mouse required for any common workflow. Start small with task-list navigation and grow outward.\n\nINITIAL SCOPE\n- Move up/down through tasks at the current zoom level: j/k and ArrowDown/ArrowUp.\n- Move into a task's subtasks (zoom in) and back out (zoom out): h/l or ArrowLeft/ArrowRight (direction to be decided — see open questions).\n- Activate the selected task (open / focus the detail pane): Enter.\n- Escape: cancel current focus state where it makes sense (e.g. blur a focused row, close a menu — Escape on the agent prompt menu already exists in src/components/TaskAgentPromptMenu/TaskAgentPromptMenu.tsx:52).\n\nThat is the v1 surface. Everything else — workspace switching, creating tasks, editing, the new resizer, command palette — comes after we agree the foundation works.\n\nCURRENT STATE\nAlmost no keyboard handling exists in src/. Single keydown listener in TaskAgentPromptMenu. No hotkey library, no focus management strategy, no roving tabindex, no aria-activedescendant pattern in place. Clean slate.\n\nWORK WITH ME\nThis task is intentionally not prescriptive past the v1 scope above. Before writing code, propose answers to these and get my sign-off:\n\n1. Library or bespoke? Candidates worth weighing: tinykeys (~600B, no deps, scoped listeners), hotkeys-js (heavier, sequences + scopes), or rolling our own dispatcher. Same heuristic as the resizer task — small + owned is fine if the surface stays simple.\n\n2. Focus management pattern. Two real options for the task list:\n   • Roving tabindex — one item has tabindex=0, others tabindex=-1, focus moves with selection. Most native, screen readers love it.\n   • aria-activedescendant — the listbox keeps focus, a child id is announced as active. Cleaner for virtualization, slightly fussier for screen readers.\n   Pick one and stick to it across all list-like surfaces (tasks, workspaces, future menus).\n\n3. Vim semantics. h/l for zoom in/out feels natural to vim users but conflicts with the left/right convention (left = parent, right = child? or the opposite?). Confirm direction before committing — it has to feel obvious.\n\n4. Where the listeners live. Per-component (composable, easy to scope) vs. a centralized hotkeys layer (single source of truth, easier discoverability). Probably per-component for v1, centralized later if the surface grows.\n\n5. Modal or not. Pure passthrough (j/k always navigate when focus is in the list) vs. modal (a normal/insert split à la real vim). Strong preference: NOT modal for v1 — modes are surprising in a GUI.\n\n6. Discoverability. Do we want a `?` cheatsheet overlay from day one, or land the bindings first and add the overlay as a follow-up?\n\nCONSTRAINTS\n- Vanilla Extract for any styling; no inline style objects.\n- Functional helpers, early returns, no forEach.\n- Bindings must not fire while a text input or contenteditable is focused (standard guard: check event.target).\n- Accessibility takes priority over vim purity. Tab order, focus rings, aria-current, aria-selected, role on lists — all correct before we celebrate the bindings.\n- Bindings should be defined as data (a small map), not scattered switch statements, so the future cheatsheet can render from the same source.\n\nACCEPTANCE (v1)\n- Can navigate the visible task list with j/k and ArrowUp/ArrowDown; selection follows focus.\n- Can zoom into a task's subtasks and back out with the agreed keys.\n- Enter activates the selected task.\n- Focus ring is visible and obvious; never lost into the void after navigation.\n- No regression for mouse users.\n- No new lint / typecheck / fallow findings.\n- A short note in AGENTS.md on the chosen library/pattern + focus-management approach, so the next surface (workspace list, command palette) follows the same shape.\n\nOUT OF SCOPE (follow-up tasks)\n- Workspace switching shortcuts.\n- Task creation / edit / delete shortcuts.\n- Command palette (Cmd+K).\n- Drag-free resizer adjustment (already covered in task hwyhgcu3 via APG splitter keys).\n- Cheatsheet overlay (may or may not be in scope — see open question 6).","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Task list + detail keyboard nav on keys branch: tinykeys bindings (j/k, h/l, arrows, Backspace), roving tabindex, lib/keyboard + taskLevel + useTaskListKeyboard, fallow clean. Enter/activate removed; AGENTS.md cheat sheet omitted.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-01T09:11:06.685Z","updated_at":"2026-06-04T08:33:32.069Z","started_at":"2026-06-04T06:37:57.692Z","completed_at":"2026-06-04T08:33:32.069Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"ktdpt2fi","parent_id":"mzb84gnf","name":"Ingredient goldens: wrap-up + expand to 10","description":"Goal: finish and harden the ingredient testing/golden workflow.\n\nScope:\n- Expand ingredient goldens to 10 total (or document why not)\n- Snapshot Spoonacular once per missing fixture (no re-fetching existing fixtures)\n- Define/maintain expected allowlists for Claude pick per ingredient\n- Ensure commands are documented and repeatable locally\n\nDone when:\n- ingredient-queries.json has the final selected set (<=10)\n- For each entry: corresponding *.spoonacular.json + *.expected.json exists\n- bun run spoonacular:ingredient:pick:golden passes for all\n- README documents snapshot vs pick runs and cost implications","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"10 ingredient goldens: Spoonacular snapshots + expected picks for all entries in ingredient-queries.json; pick golden harness passes; README documents snapshot vs pick and cost. Ti leaves uses empty Spoonacular results + no_match expected.","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"11ab3fb65c18d2d246fc1fd41ace44bf7fffe4ed","message":":wrench: spoonacular golden samples","branch":"recipe-claude","timestamp":"2026-05-16T19:51:16.754Z"}},"created_at":"2026-05-07T07:26:26.506Z","updated_at":"2026-05-16T21:43:30.348Z","started_at":"2026-05-16T19:51:16.758Z","completed_at":"2026-05-16T19:51:16.759Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"l2mowwvj","parent_id":"2evkv6xf","name":"Client consolidation: one shell + swappable sim-source; retire parallel sims","description":"Collapse the three client entry points into ONE. Today there are three factories plus query-param app-switching: createScriptlancer (default, three.js-based single-player sim), createSharedOfflineScriptlancer (?sharedsim, shared sim offline), createNetworkedScriptlancer (?server=, networked).\n\nTarget: one client shell that owns scene/renderer/camera/HUD/input, plus a swappable sim-source (\"driver\") — offline = local authoritative shared sim; online = server snapshots + client prediction/interpolation. Networking becomes a capability, not a separate app; drop the query-param-picks-a-different-factory pattern for one app with a mode. Retire the original three.js-based single-player sim once the shared sim matches its feel.\n\nGroundwork lands during Phase 3 (real fly-by-wire input moved toward the shell; a local shared-sim instance wired into the networked path). This task finishes the unification once prediction (Phase 3) and interpolation (Phase 4) are both in the networked client, so the unified client is feature-complete in both modes.\n\nStretch: runtime offline->online transition with no page reload (swap the driver, reconcile entity state on connect).\n\nSequence: after Phase 3 + Phase 4.\n\nNOTE (from Phase 3 feel-testing): move the human steering controller (yaw/pitch PIDs) INTO the shared deterministic sim and send raw input (cursor influence + throttle) over the wire instead of the PID torque output. Today the server applies the client PID output, so reconciliation cannot re-simulate the controller and its state desyncs each snapshot, producing a minor steering waver while holding a constant cursor. The textbook fix (controller is part of the replayed sim on both client and server) eliminates it and is exactly this consolidation step.\n\nNOTE (added 2026-06-29, Phase-3 offline consolidation): The OFFLINE half of this task is done. The original three.js single-player sim (createScriptlancer + createPhysicsWorld) is retired, the ?sharedsim param is gone, and the shared deterministic sim is now THE default offline mode (createScriptlancer in scriptlancer.ts runs createSinglePlayerWorld in-process). So there are now TWO entry points, not three: createScriptlancer (offline shared sim) and createNetworkedScriptlancer (online). The remaining l2mowwvj work is folding those two into one shell + swappable driver. Flagged for that merge: the offline and networked clients now carry INTENTIONAL parallel duplication (the camera-anchored reticle unproject, ship-pose snap, etc.) currently accepted in the fallow dupes baseline; the one-shell merge removes those clone groups. The offline createScriptlancer setup-factory complexity (accepted in the health baseline) should also drop once the shell splits into reusable pieces. Spectate (death-cam blend, countdown, tap respawn), mobile roll/throttle, and the cursor-exact reticle were ported onto the offline shared-sim path and live in scriptlancer.ts ready to move into the shared shell.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Consolidated the two client entry points into ONE shell + swappable sim driver. New clientShell owns renderer/scene/camera/entity-registry/input/render-loop/reticle/teardown; a SimDriver seam swaps offlineDriver (createSinglePlayerWorld + combat/AI/spectate) and onlineDriver (prediction + networkShipRegistry + remote interpolation); createSession picks a driver by mode (drivers lazy-imported so the networking bundle stays out of offline). App.tsx rewired; createScriptlancer + createNetworkedScriptlancer deleted (~-1100 lines). Removed the two parked fallow dupe clone groups (resize + reticle unproject) and reduced offline complexity below the prior health baseline (no criticals). Unified the render-camera path: online now renders through a plain look-ahead-free chase camera like offline, fixing the held-cursor view waver online. Addressed CodeRabbit review (blank ?server= guard, online partial-init cleanup, shell teardown resilience; rest skipped with reasons or tracked). Validated: vp check + 287 tests + fallow audit all green. Branch feat/client-shell-consolidation: 12a5289 (consolidation) + 9f80f1b (waver fix + review responses), pushed. Follow-ups filed under the netcode parent: Phase 4.1 shell-owned render camera (03trbq7o), Phase 4.2 offline boot-failure cleanup (s75011q0).","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"9f80f1b","message":":bug: Render online view through a look-ahead-free chase camera","branch":"feat/client-shell-consolidation","timestamp":"2026-06-30T01:58:53.143Z"}},"created_at":"2026-06-28T06:17:54.455Z","updated_at":"2026-06-30T01:58:53.147Z","started_at":"2026-06-29T23:27:36.203Z","completed_at":"2026-06-30T01:58:53.147Z","blockedBy":["31gfijwz","yc43t68n"],"blocks":["03trbq7o","s75011q0"],"children":[]}
