{"id":"r7j20xl4","parent_id":"ia40wzb6","name":"Quick prompts on workspace root panel","description":"The gdex workspace root panel (shown when a workspace is selected but no task is focused) currently displays CONFIG PATH and STORAGE PATH. This panel should also surface a Quick Prompts section, similar to what appears on individual task/subtask detail views.\n\nContext for the implementer:\n- In gdex, a \"workspace\" = a registered dex project (config + storage path pair with a label). The root panel is the view you land on after selecting a workspace from the sidebar, before navigating into any task.\n- Quick Prompts already exist on the task detail panel — this task is about bringing the same pattern to the workspace root panel.\n- The prompts on this panel are workspace-level / bootstrapping prompts (e.g. \"Create a new root task\") — the specific prompt content should be discussed with the human before implementation.\n\nCritical requirement — prompt copy must be self-contained:\nEvery quick prompt string generated from this panel will be handed to a fresh agent with zero context about any prior conversation. Prompts must be written prescriptively and include all necessary dex CLI invocation details (config path, storage path, task IDs) so the receiving agent can act without asking clarifying questions. The existing task-level quick prompts follow this pattern and should be used as a reference.\n\nPrompt testing:\nBefore finalizing any quick prompt copy, the agent should actually run the generated dex commands in the prompts to confirm they are valid and produce sensible output. Don't ship prompt strings with untested CLI invocations.\n\nPrompt lifecycle guidance (discuss with human):\nExisting quick prompts presumably already include guidance to agents on when to mark tasks as started, completed, etc. The new workspace-level prompts should do the same. As part of this task, do a pass over the existing quick prompt copy to confirm this guidance is present and consistent — discuss any gaps or inconsistencies with the human before finalizing.\n\nAlso discuss with the human before implementation:\nWhether top-level tasks within a workspace should be labeled \"Projects\" in the UI (with deeper levels called \"Tasks\" or \"Subtasks\"), or whether everything should just be called \"Tasks\" for consistency with the dex CLI. This is a separate concern from the quick prompts feature but worth settling at the same time since it affects the labels on this panel.\n\nBefore writing any code, discuss: the labeling question, the specific prompts that belong on this view, and the lifecycle guidance audit findings.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Workspace home panel shows Quick prompts (list + create root task) with isInitiallyOpen; shared QuickPromptsPanel with availability-aware selection for task detail; tightened Mark complete prompt lifecycle copy; AGENTS.md boolean naming note.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-03T02:11:27.467Z","updated_at":"2026-06-04T06:23:41.958Z","started_at":"2026-06-04T05:29:15.141Z","completed_at":"2026-06-04T06:23:41.958Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"r7m8cdls","parent_id":"2evkv6xf","name":"Asset tooling: GLB silhouette pipeline + roll-button SVGs","description":"Land the real-model silhouette pipeline from Greg's Desktop into scriptlancer on a\ndedicated branch (not main — coordinate with any in-flight work landing on main\nfirst).\n\n## Source material (copy from here; do not depend on Desktop at runtime)\n\n~/Desktop/claude-in-space/realmodel-silhouette-pipeline.zip\n\nExtract `pkg/` — it contains:\n  model_to_svg.py   — loads a 3D file via trimesh, projects to flat/shaded SVG\n  run.sh            — reproduces the flat silhouette\n  requirements.txt  — numpy, trimesh, shapely\n  README.md         — orientation flags, pose defaults, limits\n  realmodel-flat-silhouette.svg — reference output (compare your regen to this)\n\nDo NOT duplicate spaceship-fighter.glb into tools/ or commit a second copy. The\ngame already has the canonical model at:\n  apps/client/src/game/assets/models/spaceship-fighter/spaceship-fighter.glb\n\nPoint the pipeline at that path (adjust run.sh / docs accordingly).\n\n## Repo context (scriptlancer)\n\n- Bun + Vite+ monorepo; game client at apps/client/\n- Roll buttons today: apps/client/src/game/hud/rollButtons.ts uses an inline\n  L-shaped rotation-arrow SVG (ROLL_LEFT_SVG). rollButtons.css.ts styles embedded\n  svg at 30×30px; the right button mirrors via scaleX(-1) for clockwise read.\n- Root package.json declares workspaces tools/* but tools/ may not exist yet.\n- Read AGENTS.md at repo root for conventions (#/ imports, vp check, etc.).\n\n## End goal\n\nReplace the roll-button L-arrow SVG with the flat silhouette produced by this\npipeline (banked ship, currentColor, 512 viewBox). The icon should come from the\nreal in-game GLB geometry — not a hand-drawn or procedurally approximated mesh.\n\n## Goals\n\n1. tools/model-to-svg/ (or similar) — permanent home for model_to_svg.py, README\n   (adapt zip doc), requirements.txt, and a run script that references the repo\n   GLB path. Optimize for future reuse: another agent should regenerate the HUD\n   SVG without Greg's Desktop folder.\n\n2. Wire the checked-in flat SVG into rollButtons.ts (replace ROLL_LEFT_SVG).\n   Import as asset or inline — match repo patterns. Keep currentColor.\n\n3. Check in the flat SVG the client uses under apps/client/ (hud or assets path\n   that matches repo conventions).\n\n## Prove the pipeline works (required before done)\n\nRun the tool locally from the repo and regenerate the flat SVG from\napps/client/.../spaceship-fighter.glb using the locked pose defaults\n(--bank 40 --pitch 6 --spin -18 --forward=-X --up=+Y). Document the exact\ncommand in tools/README. Visually compare (or diff) output against the reference\nrealmodel-flat-silhouette.svg from the zip — minor float/path simplification\ndifferences are OK; shape and pose should match. Record the command you ran in the\ntask result when completing.\n\n## Explicitly out of scope\n\n- Committing a duplicate GLB under tools/\n- OBJ→GLB conversion or replacing the in-game 3D ship model\n- Thruster / physics collider changes\n- Multiplayer / netcode work (parent task is unrelated)\n\n## Cleanup before commit\n\n- One canonical generator + one checked-in client SVG; no stale Desktop-only paths\n- Valid tools/ workspace layout if monorepo requires package.json per workspace\n- vp check && vp test; bun run fallow:audit -- --base origin/main if touching apps/client\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- Branch (not main) with tools/ pipeline documented and runnable from repo root\n- Agent has run the pipeline and verified regen matches the reference silhouette\n- Roll buttons show the banked-ship flat SVG instead of the L-arrow","priority":1,"completed":false,"result":null,"metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-27T05:04:56.865Z","updated_at":"2026-06-27T19:02:09.351Z","started_at":"2026-06-27T19:02:09.348Z","completed_at":null,"blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"rmuexegj","parent_id":"0m493lgo","name":"Human fly-by-wire: formal Pilot implementation","description":"Complete the Pilot abstraction so the player path is symmetric with AI: each frame\na Pilot yields (localSteering, throttle) and the game loop calls applyControls —\nthe same seam createAiPilot already uses.\n\nContext (after bcohudeg):\n- Pilot / PilotFrame live in src/game/pilot/pilot.ts.\n- AI: createAiPilot → step → applyControls on aiShipPhysics.\n- Human: attachFlyByWire still owns engagement, pointer lock, reticle, chase\n  camera, and firing flags, but embeds stick+throttle inside the closure instead\n  of exposing a Pilot.\n\nSuggested steps:\n1. createHumanPilot (or equivalent) producing PilotFrame from fly-by-wire input\n   state (cursor influence, W/S throttle keys). Extract pure helpers where\n   possible; unit-test throttle ramp and steering output when engaged vs idle.\n2. Refactor attachFlyByWire into layers: event/UI shell (engagement, HUD reads)\n   + human Pilot step for flight demand when engaged (zero steering, throttle\n   holds or decays when disengaged — match current feel).\n3. scriptlancer: apply player controls via the same loop pattern as AI\n   (pilot.step → shipPhysics.applyControls per ship).\n\nOut of scope: retuning fly-by-wire feel, camera behavior, or HUD layout.\n\nConventions: #/ imports with .ts suffix, type over interface, undefined over\nnull, @sideEffect tags, pure tested math. Validate with vp check, vp test, and\nbun run fallow:audit. See AGENTS.md.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Human fly-by-wire routed through Pilot: createHumanPilot + tests; attachFlyByWire is input/camera shell; scriptlancer applies player applyControls like AI. vp check, 125 tests, fallow audit pass.","metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-25T05:34:42.417Z","updated_at":"2026-06-25T06:15:59.076Z","started_at":"2026-06-25T06:11:33.905Z","completed_at":"2026-06-25T06:15:59.076Z","blockedBy":["bcohudeg"],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"s75011q0","parent_id":"2evkv6xf","name":"Phase 4.2 — Offline driver boot-failure resource cleanup","description":"Consolidation follow-up (after l2mowwvj). On a failed offline boot (loadGameModel / createAsteroidField / initRapier / createGameAudio throws mid-factory), createOfflineDriver leaks the driver-owned resources NOT in the entity registry: the mounted dustField scene resource, the Rapier world, audio, thruster effects, and the DOM overlays (spectateOverlay, rollButtons, touchThrottleHud). createScriptlancerSession's catch calls shell.destroy(), which reclaims the registry-spawned entities (ships, indicators, asteroids), canvas, renderer, lights, and star/nebula backdrop, but NOT those driver-owned extras. Wrap createOfflineDriver's allocations with cleanup-on-failure (e.g. a cleanups-list built as resources are allocated, run in the catch before rethrowing). The online driver already does this (onlineDriver partial-init, commit 9f80f1b). Low priority: boot-failure-only path, cleared on the mandatory reload. Deferred from CodeRabbit review on the consolidation PR as disproportionate churn for that PR.","priority":3,"completed":true,"result":"Wrapped createOfflineDriver's async boot in cleanup-on-failure. A cleanups: (()=>void)[] list gets a disposer pushed right after each driver-owned NON-registry resource is allocated (dustField, audio, thruster effects, bolt/impact/explosion effects, HUD overlays, spectate overlay, world, container listeners); the factory body is wrapped in try/catch that runs the cleanups LIFO on any mid-boot throw before rethrowing, so a failed offline boot no longer leaks them. destroy() now just runs the same cleanups (consolidates the old explicit disposal list). Registry-spawned entities (ship models, indicators, asteroids) are excluded — shell.destroy()/despawnAll reclaims those; no double-dispose. Shipped in PR #37 (draft), commit 3d7c961; vp check + 287 tests + fallow all green.","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"3d7c961","message":":recycle: Shell-owned render camera + offline boot-failure cleanup","branch":"refactor/shell-render-camera","timestamp":"2026-06-30T04:39:41.098Z"}},"created_at":"2026-06-30T01:13:41.794Z","updated_at":"2026-06-30T04:39:41.103Z","started_at":"2026-06-30T03:49:47.966Z","completed_at":"2026-06-30T04:39:41.103Z","blockedBy":["l2mowwvj"],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
