{"id":"vk5bjz7z","parent_id":"zgbnfktr","name":"Blog post: tmux as the universal unlock for agents","description":"Write a blog post for greglinscheid.com about using tmux with coding agents. Output of a grilling session — framing is settled, but the future agent should PROPOSE choices to Greg (spine, title, structure) and let HIM pick. Do not be prescriptive in the post, and do not decide the open choices unilaterally.\n\nCORE THESIS\nAn agent can only read the files you hand it. It CANNOT attach to the live rendered output of a process it didn't spawn (dev server, REPL, ssh session, TUI) unless that process lives in a multiplexer it can address. tmux is the shared substrate that turns 'stuff I happen to be running' into 'stuff a third party (the agent) can read.' Frame: tmux as the universal unlock.\n\nTONE (firm constraint)\nCalm 'public journal' — Greg is not a public figure writing a manifesto. NOT prescriptive. Kill any 'you need to' / 'people are doing it wrong' / 'this is the future' framing. It's a personal 'this opened my eyes' discovery post. Match the voice of existing posts in src/content/blog (conversational, self-aware, headers-as-questions, real code blocks, casual asides).\n\nSPINE — offer these to Greg, let him pick/remix (do NOT choose):\n1. 'Your agent can only see the files you hand it — until your work lives in tmux, and then it can see your screen.'\n2. 'A multiplexer turns stuff I'm running into stuff my agent can read.'\n3. 'The agent isn't blind because it's dumb; it's blind because your terminal stream isn't addressable. tmux fixes the addressing.'\n\nTITLE — the brief originally said 'why folks who use agents NEED to be using tmux more' but Greg backed off the prescriptive framing. Propose non-prescriptive title options (e.g. 'tmux opened my eyes about agents', 'More agent users should try tmux'); let Greg pick.\n\nARC (agreed structure)\n1. The realization / framing — understated 'third eye' moment, not literally spiritual.\n2. Why agents are effectively blind — they read files, not your live streams.\n3. The primitive: 'tmux literally reading the panel.' Dumb but universal — works on anything, just rendered text (ANSI noise and all). Show the literal command (e.g. tmux capture-pane). Concrete example: agent reading a dev server / REPL output in another pane. NOTE: Greg currently has NO capture-pane/pipe-pane tooling in dotfiles — this opening is the reproducible primitive, shown as raw built-ins, not as a config to install.\n4. Escalate through other built-ins (send-keys to drive a pane, pipe-pane to stream, addressing panes/sessions). Possibly a note on agents parallelizing themselves (Greg waved at this twice — future agent should ASK whether it's in or out, don't force it).\n5. The constraint, stated honestly but not preachy: this works to the extent your work lives in the terminal/TUIs. Acknowledge briefly, don't sell terminal-maximalism.\n6. PAYOFF — the refined tool: once the flow stabilized, Greg made it deterministic. nvim-ctx (in dotfiles, ~/.local/bin/nvim-ctx) uses tmux purely as a pane-DISCOVERY/addressing layer (tmux list-panes to find the nvim pane) then talks to nvim's RPC socket (nvim --server --remote-expr) for STRUCTURED context — file, line range, the actual visual selection as JSON. The 'CMD+L / Cursor-like' analog, but via tmux+nvim. IMPORTANT distinction to make explicit in the post: capturing a pane's raw text (Power A) and using tmux to address a program then reach its own richer RPC interface (Power B) are DIFFERENT mechanisms. nvim-ctx is Power B. Don't let a reader think capture-pane gives them the nvim magic.\n7. Close: not telling anyone to change; just what opened Greg's eyes. tmux as the universal handle that unlocks both A and B — use the workflow ending as the final example.\n\nDELIVERABLE\nA 'skeleton' draft (NOT a finished post): an outline/scaffold that may contain placeholder strings like 'section on X here' or 'include image of Y here'. Place it OUTSIDE the Astro content collection (the glob loader bases on ./src/content/blog) so it does not build/publish — e.g. a drafts/ dir at repo root. Frontmatter schema when it eventually moves in: title, description, pubDate, optional updatedDate, optional heroImage.\n\nReference files: ~/.local/bin/nvim-ctx (the script), ~/.claude/skills/nvim-ctx/SKILL.md, existing posts in src/content/blog/, schema in src/content.config.ts.","priority":1,"completed":false,"result":null,"metadata":null,"created_at":"2026-06-27T20:45:48.541Z","updated_at":"2026-06-27T20:45:48.541Z","started_at":null,"completed_at":null,"blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
{"id":"w4uplxdh","parent_id":"2evkv6xf","name":"Phase 5 — Server-authoritative combat + lag compensation","description":"CONTEXT: Anti-cheat boundary; the second tricky phase. Like Phase 3, the gate is judged by FEEL/fairness, not a unit test — expect the user in the loop.\n\nINVESTIGATE: moving weapon fire, hit detection, damage, and AI fully server-side; LAG COMPENSATION (server rewinds target positions to the firer input timestamp to validate hits) using a short server-side history of entity transforms; client rendering fire/impact/explosion effects from server events only; reusing vs reworking current weaponSystem, aiPilot, and collision-audio logic behind the authority boundary.\n\nENGAGE THE USER FIRST: before implementing, agree the approach with the user (rewind window, how predicted local effects reconcile with server confirmation). Then implement, and hand BACK to the user to play-test fairness — do NOT self-mark done.\n\nOPEN QUESTIONS FOR THE USER: how far back to retain rewind history; how to reconcile predicted local weapon effects with server confirmation.\n\nREFERENCES (implement the standard pattern, do not invent one): Valve \"Source Multiplayer Networking\" / \"Latency Compensating Methods\" https://developer.valvesoftware.com/wiki/Source_Multiplayer_Networking ; Gabriel Gambetta \"Fast-Paced Multiplayer\" — Lag Compensation https://www.gabrielgambetta.com/client-server-game-architecture.html\n\nDONE WHEN: hits feel fair under latency, combat outcomes are server-decided, and a client cannot spoof hits or damage. NOTE: implement, then hand back to the user to verify the fairness gate — do not self-mark done.\n\nNOTES FROM PHASE-3 OFFLINE CONSOLIDATION (added 2026-06-29): The offline shared-sim path now runs the authoritative pieces in-process; when this phase moves them server-side, carry these over. (1) FIRE-RATE/ARC GATING — the shared weaponSystem already gates fire cadence (REFIRE_DELAY) and the gun arc, and offline this runs in-process, so a spamming client can't over-fire. Online, the server must run that same weaponSystem.update on the client's isFiring/aimPoint input and gate it there; confirm end-to-end that a client spamming fire still emits bolts only at the legal cap. (2) CLIENT-AUTHORITATIVE AIM — the client sends aimPoint, so an aim-bot is a SEPARATE cheat from over-firing; decide whether to validate/clamp aim server-side or accept it. (3) SERVER-OWNED DEATH/RESPAWN — the offline spectate (death-cam blend + countdown + tap/click respawn) is fully client-driven because offline the client IS the authority. Online, the server must own death and respawn (whether you are alive/spawned); the client keeps only the spectate PRESENTATION (overlay, death-cam, countdown) and sends a respawn REQUEST on tap, which the server grants. The offline code deliberately isolates the single authoritative action (world.respawnPlayer) as the seam — online, swap that one call for a server respawn request and leave the rest client-side.","priority":1,"completed":true,"result":"Phase 5 combat netcode: 5a (server-authoritative combat) merged; 5c (server-owned death/respawn) + 5b (lag compensation) combined in draft PR #41 off main, both self-reviewed + feel-tested good. Follow-ups: per-client RTT lag-comp (needs client view-tick) + thick-ray helper dedupe.","metadata":{"commit":{"sha":"db8a318","message":":sparkles: Manual-lead aim and online combat HUD","branch":"main","timestamp":"2026-06-30T08:41:08.947Z"}},"created_at":"2026-06-26T08:41:06.837Z","updated_at":"2026-06-30T16:33:24.154Z","started_at":"2026-06-30T04:51:55.243Z","completed_at":"2026-06-30T16:33:24.154Z","blockedBy":[],"blocks":[],"children":[]}
